The eye size, dorsal microsculpture, shape of aedeagus and antenna, as well as the presence of irregularly arranged punctuation on the elytra, place this species near C. championi (Portevin 1937) from South India, C. pecki Daffner 1988 from Japan and C. castanea Svec 2011 from China. However, C. championi has longer parameres and a less clearly sinuous outline of the aedeagus apex ( Daffner 1991 ). C. pecki has the 11th antennomere much smaller than in C. chungi . C. castanea has acute posterior angles of the pronotum and a more stocky aedeagus (
Svec 2011
).
